<mechanism wordnetid="103738472" confidence="0.8">
<plaything wordnetid="103964744" confidence="0.8">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../226/8262226.xml">
Dragonfly</link></plaything>
</mechanism>
</device>
</vehicle>
</instrumentality>
</artifact>
</automaton>
</conveyance>
 from <company wordnetid="108058098" confidence="0.8">
<institution wordnetid="108053576" confidence="0.8">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../880/1100880.xml">
WowWee</link></institution>
</company>
 have extended the market from dedicated hobbyists to the general toy market,</p>
<p>

Some helpful resources for hobbyists include The Ornithopter Design Manual, book written by Nathan Chronister, and <weblink xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.ornithopter.org">
The Ornithopter Zone web site</weblink>, which includes a large amount of information about building and flying these models.</p>

</sec>
<sec>
<st>
 Aerodynamics </st>

<p>

<indent level="1">

<it>Main article: <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../819/2819.xml">
Aerodynamics</link></it>
</indent>

As demonstrated by birds, flapping wings offer potential advantages in maneuverability and <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../649/9649.xml">
energy</link> savings compared with fixed-wing aircraft, as well as potentially vertical take-off and landing. It has been suggested that these advantages are greatest at small sizes and low flying speeds.</p>
<p>

Unlike airplanes and helicopters, the driving <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../053/290053.xml">
airfoil</link>s of the ornithopter have a flapping or oscillating motion, instead of rotary. As with helicopters, the wings usually have a combined function of providing both lift and thrust. Theoretically, the flapping wing can be set to zero <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../102/232102.xml">
angle of attack</link> on the upstroke, so it passes easily through the air. Since typically the flapping airfoils produce both lift and thrust, <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../292/2137292.xml">
drag</link>-inducing structures are minimized. These two advantages potentially allow a high degree of efficiency.</p>

